    <section class="section s2" id="s2">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="section-icon-wrap">&#128225;</div>
        <div class="section-head-text">
          <div class="section-eyebrow">Section 02 — Network Layer</div>
          <div class="section-title">Router Questions</div>
        </div>
        <span class="section-pill">15 Q&amp;A</span>
      </div>
      <div class="section-toolbar">
        <button class="toolbar-btn" onclick="expandSection('s2')">EXPAND ALL</button>
        <button class="toolbar-btn" onclick="collapseSection('s2')">COLLAPSE ALL</button>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-list" id="list-s2">

        <div class="qa-item s2" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">01</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is a router?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">A <strong>router</strong> is a Layer 3 (Network Layer) device that <strong>forwards IP packets between two or more distinct networks</strong>. It maintains routing tables to determine the optimal path for each packet. In a home or small-office context, the router connects the private LAN to the public Internet and simultaneously provides DHCP, NAT, and basic firewall services.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s2" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">02</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is the function of a router in a network?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">Core functions: <strong>Inter-network routing</strong> — forwarding packets between LAN and WAN. <strong>DHCP server</strong> — automatic IP address assignment to local devices. <strong>NAT</strong> — mapping multiple private IPs to a single public IP. <strong>Firewall / packet filtering</strong> — blocking unauthorised inbound connections. <strong>DNS relay</strong> — forwarding DNS queries to the ISP or a configured resolver. Enterprise routers additionally run dynamic routing protocols (OSPF, BGP, EIGRP).</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s2" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">03</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is a default gateway?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">The <strong>default gateway</strong> is the IP address of the router interface on the local subnet. When a device sends a packet to a destination <strong>outside its own subnet</strong>, it forwards the packet to the default gateway, which then routes it further. In most home networks this is <strong>192.168.1.1</strong> or <strong>192.168.0.1</strong>. It is configured automatically via DHCP or manually in the device's network settings.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s2" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">04</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is DHCP and what does it do?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>DHCP (Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol)</strong> — defined in RFC 2131 — automatically provisions network parameters to clients. When a device joins the network it broadcasts a DHCP Discover message; the DHCP server (typically the router) responds with an <strong>IP address, subnet mask, default gateway, and DNS server addresses</strong>. Leases are time-limited and renewed automatically, allowing IP address reuse as devices leave the network.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s2" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">05</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is NAT (Network Address Translation)?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>NAT</strong> allows an entire private network to share <strong>one public IP address</strong>. The router maintains a translation table mapping each private (source IP : port) pair to the public IP with a unique port number. Outbound packets have their source address rewritten to the public IP; inbound replies are translated back to the correct private host. This conserves IPv4 address space and provides implicit inbound security by hiding the internal network topology.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s2" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">06</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is the difference between LAN and WAN ports on a router?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>LAN ports</strong> — connect devices on the local private network (PCs, switches, printers, access points). Typically 4 × 1G RJ45 ports. Devices on LAN ports share the same broadcast domain and receive private IP addresses from the router's DHCP pool.<br><br><strong>WAN port</strong> — connects to the ISP modem or ONT (1 port). Receives the public IP address from the ISP. The router routes traffic between the WAN interface and the LAN interfaces, performing NAT in the process.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s2" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">07</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is port forwarding?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>Port forwarding</strong> (also called destination NAT) instructs the router to redirect inbound traffic arriving on a specific port from the WAN to a designated internal host and port. Example: forwarding TCP/80 to 192.168.1.50:80 makes an internal web server accessible from the internet. Commonly used for web servers, game servers, IP cameras, NVRs, FTP servers, and remote desktop services. Each forwarding rule specifies the external port, internal IP, and internal port.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s2" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">08</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is the purpose of static and dynamic IP addresses?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>Dynamic IP</strong> — assigned automatically by DHCP; may change at each lease renewal. Appropriate for end-user devices (laptops, phones) that don't need to be consistently addressable.<br><br><strong>Static IP</strong> — manually configured or assigned via a DHCP reservation; never changes. Essential for infrastructure that must always be reachable at the same address: servers, NVRs, IP cameras, network printers, and access points. Static assignment prevents connection loss caused by IP reassignment.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s2" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">09</span><span class="qa-question-text">What are the common private IP address ranges?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">Defined in <strong>RFC 1918</strong>, the three private address blocks are:<br><br>
            <strong>10.0.0.0 / 8</strong> — Class A · 16,777,216 addresses · large enterprise networks<br>
            <strong>172.16.0.0 / 12</strong> — Class B · 1,048,576 addresses · mid-size networks<br>
            <strong>192.168.0.0 / 16</strong> — Class C · 65,536 addresses · home and SMB networks<br><br>
            These addresses are not routed on the public Internet; NAT translates them at the network boundary.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s2" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">10</span><span class="qa-question-text">How can you access a router's web interface?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">Open a browser and navigate to the router's LAN IP address — typically <strong>192.168.1.1</strong> or <strong>192.168.0.1</strong> (check the label on the device). Enter the administrator credentials (default credentials are printed on the device label; they should be changed immediately). From the web GUI you can configure: DHCP, DNS, Wi-Fi SSID and security, port forwarding, firewall rules, QoS, VPN, and firmware updates.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s2" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">11</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is SSID?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>SSID (Service Set Identifier)</strong> is the human-readable <strong>name of a Wi-Fi network</strong>, broadcast by the access point in Beacon frames every 100 ms. Devices display this name in their Wi-Fi list. Up to 32 ASCII characters are permitted. The SSID can be hidden (Beacon frames omit it), but this provides minimal security since it remains visible in probe responses. Dual-band routers typically broadcast separate SSIDs for 2.4 GHz and 5 GHz bands.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s2" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">12</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is MAC filtering in routers?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>MAC filtering</strong> maintains an allow-list (or deny-list) of device hardware addresses. Only clients whose <strong>MAC address appears in the allow-list</strong> are permitted to associate with the access point. It provides an additional administrative control layer but is <strong>not a strong security measure</strong> — MAC addresses are transmitted in plaintext during association and can be spoofed by an attacker using freely available tools in seconds. Use it alongside, not instead of, strong WPA3 encryption.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s2" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">13</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is QoS (Quality of Service)?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>QoS (Quality of Service)</strong> is a set of techniques that <strong>prioritise traffic types to guarantee performance</strong> for latency-sensitive applications. The router classifies packets (by port, protocol, IP, or DSCP marking) and queues high-priority traffic — VoIP, video conferencing, real-time gaming — ahead of lower-priority traffic such as bulk file transfers. On consumer routers, QoS can be set per device or per application; on enterprise equipment, Differentiated Services (DiffServ) and traffic-shaping policies are used.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s2" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">14</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is the difference between a modem and a router?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>Modem</strong> (Modulator-Demodulator) — converts the ISP's physical signal (DSL, cable, fibre) into a digital Ethernet feed. It operates at Layer 1–2 and connects a single device to the internet. It has no routing, DHCP, or NAT intelligence.<br><br><strong>Router</strong> — distributes the internet connection to multiple devices, assigns private IPs, performs NAT, and enforces firewall policies. It operates at Layer 3. ISPs commonly supply a combined gateway device that integrates both functions.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s2" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">15</span><span class="qa-question-text">How do you secure a Wi-Fi network?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>1.</strong> Change the default admin credentials immediately.<br><strong>2.</strong> Use <strong>WPA3</strong> (or WPA2-AES at minimum); avoid WEP and TKIP.<br><strong>3.</strong> Set a strong, unique Wi-Fi passphrase (16+ characters, mixed).<br><strong>4.</strong> Disable <strong>WPS</strong> — it is vulnerable to PIN brute-force attacks.<br><strong>5.</strong> Keep router firmware updated.<br><strong>6.</strong> Enable a guest network to isolate IoT and visitor devices.<br><strong>7.</strong> Disable remote management unless operationally required.<br><strong>8.</strong> Enable the built-in firewall and review logs periodically.</div></div></div>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ══════════════ SECTION 3: SWITCH ══════════════ -->
    <section class="section s3" id="s3">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="section-icon-wrap">&#9654;</div>
        <div class="section-head-text">
          <div class="section-eyebrow">Section 03 — Data Link Layer</div>
          <div class="section-title">Switch Questions</div>
        </div>
        <span class="section-pill">15 Q&amp;A</span>
      </div>
      <div class="section-toolbar">
        <button class="toolbar-btn" onclick="expandSection('s3')">EXPAND ALL</button>
        <button class="toolbar-btn" onclick="collapseSection('s3')">COLLAPSE ALL</button>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-list" id="list-s3">

        <div class="qa-item s3" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">01</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is a network switch?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">A <strong>network switch</strong> is a Layer 2 device that connects multiple hosts within a LAN. It uses <strong>MAC addresses</strong> to make forwarding decisions, delivering frames only to the port where the destination device resides rather than broadcasting to all ports. This dedicated bandwidth per port and elimination of unnecessary traffic is the fundamental improvement over a hub, and it forms the backbone of every modern wired LAN.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s3" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">02</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is the main difference between a hub and a switch?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>Hub (Layer 1)</strong> — a passive repeater that regenerates and broadcasts every incoming electrical signal to all ports. All connected devices share the same collision domain and total bandwidth. Effectively obsolete.<br><br><strong>Switch (Layer 2)</strong> — examines the destination MAC address of each incoming frame and forwards it <strong>only to the specific port</strong> connected to the destination host. Each port operates as its own collision domain in full-duplex mode. Devices share no bandwidth with uninvolved stations, improving performance and security significantly.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s3" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">03</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is a PoE switch?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">A <strong>PoE switch</strong> supplies DC electrical power over the Ethernet cable alongside data, eliminating the need for a separate power adapter at the remote device. The switch acts as the <strong>Power Sourcing Equipment (PSE)</strong>, the camera or phone as the <strong>Powered Device (PD)</strong>. Key standards: <strong>IEEE 802.3af</strong> (up to 15.4 W), <strong>802.3at / PoE+</strong> (up to 30 W), <strong>802.3bt / PoE++</strong> (up to 90 W). The switch's total power budget determines how many ports can be powered simultaneously.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s3" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">04</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is VLAN and why is it used?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>VLAN (Virtual LAN)</strong> logically partitions a single physical switch into multiple isolated broadcast domains — without additional hardware. Use cases: isolating the CCTV/IoT network from the corporate user network for <strong>security</strong>; separating voice and data to reduce broadcast traffic and improve <strong>performance</strong>; grouping users by department regardless of physical location; and simplifying compliance with data-segregation requirements. VLANs are configured per-port on managed switches and tagged (IEEE 802.1Q) across trunk links.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s3" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">05</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is the difference between managed and unmanaged switches?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>Unmanaged switch</strong> — factory-configured, plug-and-play. No management interface. Fixed feature set: basic Layer 2 switching only. Suitable for small offices, home networks, or extending a LAN with no configuration requirements.<br><br><strong>Managed switch</strong> — configurable via CLI (SSH/console), web GUI, or SNMP. Supports VLANs, QoS (802.1p), STP/RSTP, LACP (link aggregation), port mirroring, SNMP monitoring, access control lists, and storm control. Essential for enterprise, data centre, and multi-segment networks requiring control, visibility, and network policy enforcement.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s3" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">06</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is a MAC address table?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">The <strong>MAC address table</strong> (Content-Addressable Memory / CAM table) is a hardware-accelerated database the switch maintains in fast TCAM. It maps each <strong>source MAC address → ingress port number</strong>. The switch populates the table dynamically by inspecting the source MAC of every received frame. When forwarding, it looks up the destination MAC; a cache hit delivers the frame to the correct port only. Cache misses trigger flooding. Entries age out after an inactivity timer (typically 300 seconds) to stay current.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s3" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">07</span><span class="qa-question-text">How does a switch forward data packets?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>1. Learn</strong> — record source MAC and ingress port in the CAM table.<br><strong>2. Lookup</strong> — search CAM for destination MAC.<br><strong>3. Forward</strong> — if found, send frame to that specific port only (unicast).<br><strong>4. Flood</strong> — if not found (unknown unicast) or if destination is a broadcast/multicast, send out all ports except the ingress port.<br><br>Modern switches use <strong>store-and-forward</strong> (full frame buffered before forwarding — validates CRC) or <strong>cut-through</strong> (forwarding begins after reading the destination MAC — lower latency but forwards corrupt frames).</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s3" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">08</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is a broadcast domain?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">A <strong>broadcast domain</strong> is the set of network devices that receive a Layer 2 broadcast frame (destination MAC FF:FF:FF:FF:FF:FF) from any member of the group. All ports on a switch (without VLANs) belong to the same broadcast domain. <strong>Routers and VLANs</strong> define domain boundaries. Large broadcast domains degrade performance as every device must process each broadcast. Proper segmentation using VLANs and routing reduces broadcast overhead significantly.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s3" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">09</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is a collision domain?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">A <strong>collision domain</strong> is a network segment in which two simultaneous transmissions will result in a collision, corrupting both frames. Hubs place all connected devices in a single collision domain. Switches give each port its <strong>own collision domain</strong>. In full-duplex operation (standard on all modern switch ports), transmit and receive paths are completely separate circuits, making collisions physically impossible — CSMA/CD is not needed.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s3" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">10</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is link aggregation?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>Link Aggregation</strong> (IEEE 802.3ad, controlled by <strong>LACP</strong> — Link Aggregation Control Protocol) bundles multiple physical Ethernet ports into a single logical interface. Benefits: <strong>Increased bandwidth</strong> (4 × 1 Gbps = 4 Gbps logical throughput), <strong>load balancing</strong> across member links (by src/dst MAC, IP, or port-based hashing), and <strong>high availability</strong> — the logical link remains active if a physical member fails. Requires both sides (switch-to-switch or switch-to-server) to support and negotiate LACP.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s3" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">11</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is the function of STP (Spanning Tree Protocol)?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>STP (IEEE 802.1D)</strong> prevents <strong>Layer 2 forwarding loops</strong> in switched networks with redundant paths. Without it, a single broadcast frame would circulate indefinitely — a broadcast storm — consuming all available bandwidth and crashing the network within seconds. STP elects a root bridge, calculates the shortest path to it from each switch, and places redundant ports in a <strong>Blocking</strong> state. <strong>RSTP (802.1w)</strong> converges in under a second vs STP's 30–50 seconds. <strong>MSTP (802.1s)</strong> extends this to multiple spanning tree instances per VLAN group.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s3" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">12</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is the purpose of trunk ports?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">A <strong>trunk port</strong> (IEEE 802.1Q) carries frames from <strong>multiple VLANs simultaneously</strong> over a single physical link between switches, between a switch and a router, or between a switch and a server. Each frame is tagged with a 4-byte 802.1Q header containing the VLAN ID (1–4094), allowing the receiving device to identify and process it correctly. The <strong>native VLAN</strong> (typically VLAN 1) sends frames untagged. Trunk ports are critical to inter-switch VLAN extension without requiring separate physical cables per VLAN.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s3" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">13</span><span class="qa-question-text">How do you check the status of ports on a switch?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">CLI commands on Cisco IOS: <strong>show interfaces</strong> (detailed counters, errors), <strong>show interfaces status</strong> (brief connected/notconnect/disabled summary), <strong>show mac address-table</strong> (learned MACs per port/VLAN). Physical LED indicators: <strong>green</strong> = link active / traffic, <strong>amber</strong> = port blocked by STP or an error state, <strong>off</strong> = no device connected or port administratively shut down. SNMP-based monitoring platforms (Zabbix, SolarWinds, PRTG) poll these OIDs continuously for dashboard visibility and alerting.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s3" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">14</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is loop prevention in networking?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">Mechanisms to prevent Layer 2 forwarding loops:<br><strong>STP / RSTP</strong> — the primary protocol; detects and blocks redundant paths.<br><strong>BPDUGuard</strong> — shuts down an access port immediately if it receives an STP BPDU, preventing rogue switches from influencing the topology.<br><strong>Storm Control</strong> — rate-limits broadcast/multicast/unknown-unicast traffic on a port, mitigating the impact of a storm before it saturates the network.<br><strong>Loop Guard</strong> — prevents a port from becoming a designated or root port due to BPDU loss, protecting against unidirectional link failures.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s3" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">15</span><span class="qa-question-text">How do you connect multiple switches together?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">Use <strong>uplink ports</strong> (standard or dedicated gigabit/10G ports) with Cat6 or SFP fibre cables in a hierarchical (core–distribution–access) or flat topology. Configure <strong>trunk ports (802.1Q)</strong> on the inter-switch links to carry all required VLANs. Enable <strong>RSTP</strong> on all switches to prevent loops. For scale-out, use <strong>stack cables</strong> (proprietary) to merge multiple physical switches into one logical chassis — simplifying management and eliminating STP between stack members. Always design for redundancy using dual uplinks with LACP where the budget permits.</div></div></div>

      </div>
    </section>

