        <div class="section-head-text">
          <div class="section-eyebrow">Section 04 — Endpoint Devices</div>
          <div class="section-title">Webcam Questions</div>
        </div>
        <span class="section-pill">15 Q&amp;A</span>
      </div>
      <div class="section-toolbar">
        <button class="toolbar-btn" onclick="expandSection('s4')">EXPAND ALL</button>
        <button class="toolbar-btn" onclick="collapseSection('s4')">COLLAPSE ALL</button>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-list" id="list-s4">

        <div class="qa-item s4" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">01</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is a webcam and how does it work?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">A <strong>webcam</strong> is a compact digital video camera that connects directly to a computer and streams live video. Light enters through the lens and strikes a <strong>CMOS image sensor</strong>, which converts photons into an analogue electrical signal. An on-chip <strong>ISP (Image Signal Processor)</strong> performs noise reduction, white balance, and colour correction before the frame is compressed (H.264, MJPEG, or H.265) and transmitted via USB to the host computer, which presents it as a standard UVC video device.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s4" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">02</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is the difference between a webcam and an IP camera?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>Webcam</strong> — peripheral device connected via USB to a host PC. The PC provides processing, storage, and network access. Range is limited to USB cable length. Suitable for video calls and local streaming.<br><br><strong>IP camera</strong> — standalone networked device with its own CPU, firmware, and web interface. Connects to a LAN via Ethernet or Wi-Fi. Streams video independently over RTSP. Can be viewed remotely over the internet, integrate with an NVR, and operate 24 / 7 without a dedicated PC.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s4" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">03</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is FPS in webcams?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>FPS (Frames Per Second)</strong> is the number of discrete still images the camera captures and outputs each second to form a video stream. <strong>24 fps</strong> — cinematic threshold for perceived motion. <strong>30 fps</strong> — standard for video conferencing and web streaming. <strong>60 fps</strong> — smoother motion; preferred for gaming content and high-motion presentations. Higher frame rates demand more USB bandwidth, CPU processing, and network throughput. Most conferencing platforms cap ingest at 30 fps regardless of camera capability.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s4" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">04</span><span class="qa-question-text">What resolutions are common in webcams?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>480p (SD)</strong> — 640 × 480 — entry-level; adequate for basic internal calls.<br><strong>720p (HD)</strong> — 1280 × 720 — standard budget webcam output.<br><strong>1080p (Full HD)</strong> — 1920 × 1080 — current professional benchmark; sharp and widely supported.<br><strong>1440p (QHD / 2K)</strong> — 2560 × 1440 — high-end prosumer devices.<br><strong>4K (UHD)</strong> — 3840 × 2160 — premium content creation; requires USB 3.0 and significant CPU bandwidth.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s4" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">05</span><span class="qa-question-text">How do you install and configure a webcam on a PC?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>1.</strong> Connect the USB cable to any available USB port. <strong>2.</strong> Windows 10/11 auto-installs drivers for all <strong>UVC-compliant</strong> webcams — no manual installation required. <strong>3.</strong> Confirm detection: Device Manager → Cameras / Imaging Devices. <strong>4.</strong> Open the Windows Camera app or launch a video conferencing tool and select the webcam as the active camera device. <strong>5.</strong> Adjust resolution, frame rate, exposure, and white balance in the manufacturer's companion software or directly within the conferencing platform settings.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s4" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">06</span><span class="qa-question-text">What ports or interfaces do webcams use?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>USB 2.0</strong> — 480 Mbps; sufficient for up to 1080p 30fps with MJPEG or H.264 compression.<br><strong>USB 3.0 / 3.1</strong> — 5–10 Gbps; required for uncompressed 4K output.<br><strong>USB-C</strong> — increasingly used on modern premium webcams; supports USB 3.x speeds and can deliver power simultaneously.<br><strong>HDMI → Capture card</strong> — used with DSLR / mirrorless cameras as webcam sources for broadcast-quality output.<br><strong>Ethernet / Wi-Fi</strong> — network-attached conference room cameras (e.g., Logitech Rally, Poly Studio).</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s4" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">07</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is autofocus in a webcam?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>Autofocus (AF)</strong> uses continuous analysis of image sharpness (contrast detection) or a dedicated IR sensor to drive a miniature voice-coil motor that adjusts the lens position, maintaining a sharp image as the subject moves. <strong>Fixed-focus</strong> webcams are pre-set at the factory to a fixed focal distance (typically 0.5–1 m) — they are cheaper but produce soft images at closer distances. <strong>AI-based face-tracking AF</strong> in premium webcams (Logitech Brio, Dell UltraSharp) detects faces and prioritises them as the focus target.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s4" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">08</span><span class="qa-question-text">What are common uses of webcams?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">Video conferencing (Zoom, Microsoft Teams, Google Meet), corporate town halls and remote work, online education and live tutoring, live streaming and content creation (YouTube, Twitch), telemedicine and remote patient consultations, online proctoring for certification exams, facial recognition and Windows Hello biometric sign-in, and PC-based motion-activated security monitoring using software such as iSpy or Blue Iris.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s4" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">09</span><span class="qa-question-text">What factors affect webcam image quality?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>Image sensor</strong> size and generation (larger sensor = better low-light performance). <strong>Lens quality</strong> — glass elements, aperture (wider f-number = better in low light). <strong>Resolution and FPS</strong>. <strong>ISP quality</strong> — noise reduction, HDR tone-mapping, and auto-exposure algorithms. <strong>Compression codec</strong> — H.264 retains more detail per bit than MJPEG. <strong>Environmental lighting</strong> — the single most impactful variable; a ring light or diffused key light dramatically improves output from even a mid-range webcam.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s4" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">10</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is a USB driver and why is it needed for webcams?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">A <strong>USB driver</strong> is the kernel-mode software component that abstracts the hardware interface, allowing the operating system and applications to communicate with the webcam using standard APIs rather than device-specific register-level commands. The <strong>USB Video Class (UVC)</strong> standard defines a common driver interface that all compliant webcams implement — enabling Windows, macOS, and Linux to operate them with inbox (built-in OS) drivers. Non-UVC webcams require a vendor-supplied driver package.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s4" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">11</span><span class="qa-question-text">How can you test if a webcam is working?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>Windows:</strong> Start menu → Camera app; or Device Manager → Cameras for driver status. <strong>Browser test:</strong> webcamtests.com (no install required). <strong>OBS Studio:</strong> Add a Video Capture Device source and check the preview. <strong>macOS:</strong> Photo Booth or QuickTime → New Movie Recording. <strong>Linux:</strong> <code>v4l2-ctl --list-devices</code> to enumerate; Cheese or VLC for preview. Key check: confirm no other application holds an exclusive lock on the device simultaneously.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s4" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">12</span><span class="qa-question-text">What software is used for webcam recording or streaming?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>OBS Studio</strong> — open-source industry standard for streaming and local recording; supports scenes, overlays, and multi-source composition. <strong>Streamlabs</strong> — OBS-based with built-in monetisation tools. <strong>XSplit Broadcaster</strong> — professional streaming with advanced audio mixing. <strong>ManyCam</strong> — virtual camera with effects, suitable for multi-platform simultaneous streaming. <strong>NVIDIA Broadcast</strong> — AI-powered noise removal and background blur for RTX GPU users. <strong>Zoom / Teams / Meet</strong> — integrated conferencing with recording to cloud or local disk.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s4" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">13</span><span class="qa-question-text">What causes a webcam to not be detected?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">Likely causes in order of frequency: <strong>Faulty or loose USB cable</strong> — reseat or replace. <strong>Defective USB port</strong> — test on a different port. <strong>Driver corruption</strong> — uninstall in Device Manager → reinstall. <strong>Exclusive device lock</strong> — another application is using the camera; close it. <strong>OS privacy policy</strong> — Windows Settings → Privacy → Camera → allow app access. <strong>Camera disabled</strong> in Device Manager or via a hardware privacy shutter/switch. <strong>Hardware failure</strong> — test on a second PC to isolate.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s4" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">14</span><span class="qa-question-text">How do you update webcam drivers?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>Method 1 — Device Manager:</strong> Right-click the device → Update driver → Search automatically for drivers.<br><strong>Method 2 — Manufacturer website:</strong> Download the latest signed driver package directly from Logitech, Microsoft, Razer, etc. — the most reliable method.<br><strong>Method 3 — Windows Update:</strong> Settings → Windows Update → Advanced options → Optional updates → Driver updates.<br><strong>Method 4 — Companion software:</strong> Logitech G Hub, Razer Synapse, and similar tools manage driver and firmware updates automatically.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s4" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">15</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is the role of a microphone in webcams?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">The built-in microphone provides an integrated audio capture solution, presenting the webcam to the OS as both a UVC video device and a UAC (USB Audio Class) audio device. Entry-level webcams include a single omnidirectional electret capsule — functional but susceptible to echo and background noise. Mid-range models offer dual mics with <strong>beamforming</strong> to focus on the speaker. Premium models add <strong>DSP-based noise suppression and echo cancellation</strong>. For broadcast or studio-quality audio, a dedicated USB or XLR microphone is always preferred.</div></div></div>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ══════════════ SECTION 5: CCTV ══════════════ -->
    <section class="section s5" id="s5">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="section-icon-wrap">&#127910;</div>
        <div class="section-head-text">
          <div class="section-eyebrow">Section 05 — Surveillance Systems</div>
          <div class="section-title">CCTV &amp; IP Camera Questions</div>
        </div>
        <span class="section-pill">20 Q&amp;A</span>
      </div>
      <div class="section-toolbar">
        <button class="toolbar-btn" onclick="expandSection('s5')">EXPAND ALL</button>
        <button class="toolbar-btn" onclick="collapseSection('s5')">COLLAPSE ALL</button>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-list" id="list-s5">

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">01</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is an IP camera?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">An <strong>IP camera</strong> is a self-contained network device that captures video, encodes it using H.264 or H.265, and transmits the compressed stream over a standard IP network (Ethernet or Wi-Fi). Each camera has its own IP address, web-based configuration interface, and RTSP streaming endpoint. IP cameras can be managed directly or integrated with an NVR and viewed remotely over the internet, making them the foundation of all modern digital video surveillance systems.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">02</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is the difference between an analog camera and an IP camera?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>Analog camera</strong> — transmits a continuous composite video signal over coaxial cable to a DVR, which digitises and records it. Resolution is limited (typically 720p–1080p with HD-TVI/AHD). No direct network access; remote viewing requires DVR port-forwarding. Simple and cost-effective for small systems.<br><br><strong>IP camera</strong> — outputs a pre-encoded digital stream over Ethernet. Resolution extends to 4K/8MP and beyond. Remote access is native. Supports two-way audio, built-in analytics, PoE, encryption, and ONVIF interoperability. Scalable and feature-rich.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">03</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is PoE (Power over Ethernet)?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>PoE</strong> delivers <strong>DC power and data over a single Cat5e/Cat6 cable</strong>, eliminating the need for a separate power supply at each camera. The PoE switch (PSE — Power Sourcing Equipment) negotiates power with the camera (PD — Powered Device) using a detection and classification handshake. Standards: <strong>802.3af</strong> = max 15.4 W per port, <strong>802.3at (PoE+)</strong> = max 30 W, <strong>802.3bt (Hi-PoE / PoE++)</strong> = up to 90 W for PTZ cameras and multi-radio APs. The switch's total power budget must not be exceeded.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">04</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is the default IP address of most IP cameras?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">Manufacturer defaults: <strong>Hikvision</strong> — 192.168.1.64 &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Dahua</strong> — 192.168.1.108 &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Axis</strong> — 192.168.0.90 &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Uniview</strong> — 192.168.1.30 &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Hanwha</strong> — 192.168.1.100. Always verify against the camera label or documentation. To access the camera GUI initially, the installer PC must be set to an IP in the same subnet. Use an IP discovery tool (SADP, Advanced IP Scanner) to locate cameras on the network without knowing their IPs in advance.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">05</span><span class="qa-question-text">What software tools are used to find camera IPs?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>SADP</strong> (Hikvision) — detects Hikvision and Dahua devices; supports remote password reset via XML. <strong>ConfigTool</strong> (Dahua) — discovery and bulk configuration. <strong>ONVIF Device Manager</strong> — discovers any ONVIF-compliant camera brand-agnostically. <strong>Advanced IP Scanner</strong> (Windows) — scans a range and reports open ports and hostnames. <strong>Angry IP Scanner</strong> (cross-platform) — fast and lightweight. <strong>Nmap</strong> — advanced, can fingerprint device type and open service ports. Manufacturer mobile apps (Hik-Connect, DMSS) also perform discovery on local networks.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">06</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is ONVIF?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>ONVIF (Open Network Video Interface Forum)</strong> is an industry consortium and open standard (published as ONVIF Profiles) that defines a common communication protocol for IP cameras and video management systems. An <strong>ONVIF Profile S</strong> camera can stream video and deliver PTZ control and motion events to any Profile S-compliant NVR, regardless of manufacturer. This interoperability protects the customer's investment and simplifies integration in multi-vendor environments. Major profiles: <strong>Profile S</strong> (streaming), <strong>Profile T</strong> (H.265, analytics), <strong>Profile G</strong> (recording).</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">07</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is the function of an NVR?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">An <strong>NVR (Network Video Recorder)</strong> connects to IP cameras over the LAN, pulls their RTSP streams, and writes them to one or more internal HDDs. Key functions: <strong>Multi-channel recording</strong> (continuous, scheduled, or motion-triggered), <strong>live view and playback</strong> via local HDMI output or remote client, <strong>event management</strong> (motion alerts, email/push notifications), <strong>user access control</strong> (role-based authentication), and <strong>remote access</strong> via web browser or mobile app. Enterprise NVRs support RAID storage, redundant power supplies, and video analytics.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">08</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is RTSP?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>RTSP (Real-Time Streaming Protocol)</strong> — RFC 2326 — is an application-layer protocol that establishes and controls media delivery sessions between a streaming server (camera) and a client (NVR, VLC, browser plugin). It operates over TCP/554 by default. RTSP negotiates the stream parameters; the actual video payload is typically transported via <strong>RTP (Real-time Transport Protocol)</strong> over UDP. Standard URL format: <code>rtsp://admin:password@192.168.1.64:554/Streaming/Channels/101</code> (main stream), <code>/201</code> (sub-stream).</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">09</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is motion detection in IP cameras?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>Pixel-based motion detection</strong> compares consecutive frames and triggers an alarm when the number of changed pixels in a defined region exceeds a configured sensitivity threshold. Limitations: high false-alarm rate from lighting changes, foliage, and rain. <strong>Deep-learning analytics</strong> (available in current Hikvision, Dahua, Axis cameras) uses a convolutional neural network running on the camera's SoC to classify detected objects as human, vehicle, or animal — dramatically reducing false alarms. Triggered actions: record a video clip, capture a snapshot, activate an alarm output, send email / push notification.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">10</span><span class="qa-question-text">How can you view a camera remotely over the Internet?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>Port Forwarding:</strong> Forward required ports (80, 443, 554, 8000) through the router to the NVR/camera LAN IP. Access via public IP + DDNS hostname. Requires a DDNS service to handle dynamic public IPs.<br><br><strong>P2P / Cloud:</strong> Camera or NVR registers with the manufacturer's cloud relay server. Connect using the device's UID (QR code). No router configuration needed. Simpler, but depends on the manufacturer's cloud infrastructure remaining operational.<br><br><strong>VPN:</strong> Connect a remote device to the home/office network via VPN (OpenVPN, WireGuard). Access cameras as if local. Most secure option; no ports exposed directly to the internet.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">11</span><span class="qa-question-text">What ports are commonly used by IP cameras?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>TCP 80 / 8080</strong> — HTTP web interface and CGI API.<br><strong>TCP 443</strong> — HTTPS encrypted web interface.<br><strong>TCP 554</strong> — RTSP streaming session establishment.<br><strong>UDP varies</strong> — RTP media transport (dynamic ports negotiated via RTSP).<br><strong>TCP 8000</strong> — Hikvision SDK (iVMS-4200 and mobile app).<br><strong>TCP 37777</strong> — Dahua SDK.<br><strong>UDP 3478</strong> — STUN protocol for P2P NAT traversal.<br>These ports must be opened in the local firewall and forwarded through the router for external access.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">12</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is DDNS and why is it used?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>DDNS (Dynamic DNS)</strong> maps a fixed domain name (e.g., mysite.ddns.net) to a public IP address that changes periodically when the ISP re-assigns it. A DDNS client running on the router or NVR detects the IP change and updates the DNS record at the DDNS provider within seconds. This ensures that external users and applications can always reach the NVR / camera system using the same hostname, regardless of the current public IP. Popular providers: No-IP, DynDNS, DuckDNS, and built-in services offered by Hikvision (HiDDNS) and Dahua.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">13</span><span class="qa-question-text">How do you reset an IP camera?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>Hardware reset:</strong> With the camera powered on, locate the reset button (typically a pinhole labelled RESET on the body or tail cable). Press and hold with a straightened paperclip for 10–30 seconds until the IR LEDs flash or the camera audibly clicks, indicating a reboot to factory state. This restores the default IP address, username (admin), and password. After the reset, use SADP or an IP scanner to rediscover the camera and configure new credentials before deploying. Note: Some cameras require SADP to reset the password without a hardware button (Hikvision's export-version cameras).</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">14</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is the difference between PoE and non-PoE cameras?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>PoE camera:</strong> A single Cat5e/6 cable delivers both network data and DC power from the PoE switch to the camera. Installation is cleaner, faster, and more cost-effective — no separate power cabling or outlet at each camera position. Ideal for ceiling-mounted and outdoor cameras where AC power is unavailable.<br><br><strong>Non-PoE camera:</strong> Requires a separate 12 V DC or 24 V AC power supply cable in addition to the network cable. Two cables must be routed to each location. Necessary when PoE infrastructure is absent or when the camera's power requirement exceeds the PoE budget of the available switch.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">15</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is a P2P connection in CCTV systems?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>P2P (Peer-to-Peer)</strong> is a cloud-assisted NAT traversal method. The camera or NVR registers with the manufacturer's relay server using a unique <strong>device UID</strong> (printed as a QR code on the device). When a remote viewer opens the mobile app and scans or enters the UID, the relay server brokers a direct connection between the app and the device through NAT — without requiring the user to configure port forwarding or DDNS. The trade-off: dependency on the manufacturer's cloud service uptime and data routing through third-party infrastructure. Relevant apps: <strong>Hik-Connect</strong> (Hikvision), <strong>DMSS</strong> (Dahua), <strong>iCSee</strong> (generic).</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">16</span><span class="qa-question-text">How can you configure an IP camera manually?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>1.</strong> Connect camera to a switch or directly to the PC via Cat6. <strong>2.</strong> Run SADP or an IP scanner to discover the camera's current IP. <strong>3.</strong> Set the PC's NIC to the same subnet temporarily (e.g., 192.168.1.100 / 24). <strong>4.</strong> Open the camera IP in a web browser — use IE/Edge with IE compatibility mode for older firmware; modern firmware supports Chrome/Firefox. <strong>5.</strong> Log in with default credentials. <strong>6.</strong> Configure: static IP, video stream (codec, resolution, bitrate, frame rate), recording schedule, motion detection zones, email/FTP actions, and change the default password.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">17</span><span class="qa-question-text">What is a static IP and why use it for cameras?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">A <strong>static IP</strong> is a manually assigned, permanent IP address that does not change between reboots or power cycles. IP cameras and NVRs must use static IPs (or DHCP reservations) because the NVR stores each camera's IP in its channel configuration. If DHCP reassigns a different address to a camera after a reboot, the NVR's stored IP becomes invalid and the channel goes offline. Assign static IPs outside the DHCP pool range to prevent conflicts, and document the entire IP address plan for the installation.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">18</span><span class="qa-question-text">What causes an IP camera to go offline?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer">Root causes in order of likelihood: <strong>Cable fault</strong> — physical damage, loose RJ45, corroded contacts. <strong>IP address conflict</strong> — another device acquired the same IP. <strong>DHCP reassignment</strong> — the camera was not set to static IP. <strong>Incorrect NVR channel settings</strong> — IP, port, protocol, username, or password mismatch after a camera reset. <strong>PoE power budget exceeded</strong> — adding a new camera pushed the switch over its power limit. <strong>Firmware crash</strong> — camera requires a power-cycle reboot. <strong>Hardware failure</strong> — verify by testing on a different port/switch with a known-good cable.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">19</span><span class="qa-question-text">How do you add a camera to an NVR?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>Auto-scan / Plug-and-Play:</strong> On NVRs with built-in PoE ports, connecting a camera to a PoE port auto-discovers and adds it to the next available channel — the simplest method.<br><strong>Network scan:</strong> Go to Camera Management → Add Device → Auto-scan. The NVR searches its subnet and lists discovered cameras. Select and add with credentials.<br><strong>Manual entry:</strong> Enter the camera's IP address, port number, protocol (private SDK or ONVIF), username, and password directly. Used when the camera is on a different subnet or VLAN and must be added via its exact address.</div></div></div>

        <div class="qa-item s5" onclick="toggleItem(this)"><div class="qa-q"><span class="qa-index">20</span><span class="qa-question-text">What are the advantages of IP cameras over analog cameras?</span><span class="qa-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></div><div class="qa-body"><div class="qa-answer"><strong>Resolution</strong> — up to 4K/8MP vs 1080p max on HD-TVI analog. <strong>Digital zoom</strong> — higher resolution allows deep crop without resolution loss. <strong>PoE</strong> — single cable for data and power. <strong>Remote access</strong> — native internet accessibility without DVR dependency. <strong>Two-way audio</strong> — built-in microphone and speaker support. <strong>AI analytics</strong> — on-camera deep-learning for human/vehicle detection, facial recognition, licence plate recognition. <strong>Encryption</strong> — TLS/HTTPS for secure video transport. <strong>Scalability</strong> — add cameras by running Cat6; no coax infrastructure needed. <strong>ONVIF interoperability</strong> — mix brands freely.</div></div></div>

